Imagine a web page that is very long and consists of many sections (for example, a single-page HTML specification). If a user requests a specific section (such as page.html#section7), can the Web server send that section first and then the rest?
Flow order:
1. From the beginning of the HTML document to the <body> tag
2. The HTML code for Section 7
3. The HTML code for Sections 1, 2, and 3
The browser must ensure that Sections 1 through 6 are inserted above Section 7 on the web page.
Is this reasonable? Will it be useful?
My goal is to have the linked section (#section7) render as quickly as possible without having to reimplement it using JavaScript or similar techniques. I want a very long HTML document, but the linked section should still render quickly. This can be achieved simply with HTML.
The content can be streamed in this way, and then the browser will insert each <contents> element into the corresponding <div> element.
<div id="sec1"></div>
<div id="sec2"></div>
Etc.
<div id="sec7">section 7…</div>
<contents for="sec1">section 1…</contents>
<contents for="sec2">section 2…</contents>
etc.
Although the streaming order is out of sequence, the browser will assemble the HTML document in order.
@user22 It's actually possible to reorder the document content without using JavaScript. However, if you want the server to do something, you can't use the URL's hash fragment anymore; instead, you have to use query string parameters to tell the server which part you want to see first. As for reordering the page content, you have the following options:
1. Using CSS
2. Using templates with slots
@user23 You're right. The issue lies in the inconsistency between the visual order (what the user sees) and the DOM order. If HTML could support out-of-order streaming, and the browser could arrange the content in order into the DOM, that might be very useful.
However, the slot method seems promising. I'll try it out.
@user22 Oh, are you trying to have the browser automatically correct the DOM order?
@user23 You're right, that's exactly what I'm thinking. The only reason for sending Section 7 first is to allow the user to see it as soon as possible. If we could achieve this without affecting the DOM order, that would be great, so the browser could ensure the final DOM order matches the visual order.
In other words, send Section 7 first, but the final result (DOM and visual appearance) should be exactly the same as if all sections were transmitted in order.
@user22 @user33 You can check out PHOOOS without using JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
